            And You Can Help!</p>
            <br>
        <p>As winter approaches and temperatures drop, many homeless people seek shelter to escape the cold, but most communities lack comprehensive cold-weather response plans, leaving significant gaps in accessibility. In rural areas, shelters often lack the resources to cope with increased demand, and many cities only provide expanded winter services during specific months or when temperatures fall below arbitrary thresholds. However, hypothermia can occur even in temperatures as mild as 50Â°F, leaving many without adequate protection. Without a well-organized winter plan, homeless shelters may be unable to accommodate the influx of people, forcing many to remain on the streets where they are at heightened risk for exposure-related conditions like hypothermia and frostbite, which can be life-threatening. Expanded homeless services and additional shelter capacity are essential to meet the increased need during the winter months.</p>
